    "Richard B. Vinson": "Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` employs three verbs,\nwhich taken together express the urgency of his letter: \u201cI am\nwriting to you; . . . I am trying to arouse your sincere intention by\nreminding you.\u201d The `[group_Word_Luk_1]` testament genre is rooted in the assumed\nurgency of the author whose impending death demands that he\nmake a final contact with his audience. The `[group_Word_Luk_1]` urgency in 2 Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` is\nheightened by its subject matter\u2014the Parousia and judgment\u2014\nand by the presence of false teachers in the community. Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]`\u2019s\n[v_2Pe_1_14] predicted death (2 Pet 1:14), his convictions about \u201cthe power and\ncoming of our Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ\u201d (1:16), and his warning that\n\u201cthere will be [or are9] false teachers among you\u201d (2:1), are ample\nreasons to issue a second reminder as the letter draws to a close.\nWhile the reminder generally has to do with Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]`\u2019s testament, it\nspecifically refers to \u201cthe words spoken in the past by the holy\nprophets, and the commandment of the Lord and Savior spoken\nthrough your apostles\u201d (",
